  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_360419807" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/360419807" />
    <a title="zxvasdf" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2882638-zxvasdf"><img alt="zxvasdf" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1309066617p2/2882638.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/360419807?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="zxvasdf" class="user" itemprop="url" name="zxvasdf" href="/user/show/2882638-zxvasdf">zxvasdf</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2882638-zxvasdf?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer360419807" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11925806252909993516">This has got me scratching my head at the definition of cyberpunk. The picture everyone has is pretty much console cowboys navigating some virtual reality dreamscape from a gritty rough and tumble noirish realspace. If that&apos;s cyberpunk, then Sterling has taken the pretension way past its defined forms.<br/><br/>Schismatrix is centrally about a political and violent conflict between two general factions of humanity, one of whom prefer genetic alterations over the cybernetic modifications of the other. Our </span>
  <span id="freeText11925806252909993516" style="display:none">This has got me scratching my head at the definition of cyberpunk. The picture everyone has is pretty much console cowboys navigating some virtual reality dreamscape from a gritty rough and tumble noirish realspace. If that's cyberpunk, then Sterling has taken the pretension way past its defined forms.<br /><br />Schismatrix is centrally about a political and violent conflict between two general factions of humanity, one of whom prefer genetic alterations over the cybernetic modifications of the other. Our protagonist is the exiled Abelard Lindsay, the shamed scion of a wealthy family. His life is used as a focal point (and catalyst!) for the panorama that is the Shaper and Mechanist conflict. <br /><br />The Schismatrix future probably seemed strange to the reader when it was first published, but this love letter to the future is something the contemporary reader can appreciate and savor. There are ideas galore that give you hope, that maybe, just maybe tomorrow will be stranger. <br /><br />Space is the ultimate frontier. It cannot be regulated, and in Schismatrix, there are countless of factions that can be generalized as Shaper and Mechanist and, eventually, something else as the galaxy does its inexorable turn in Time. Finishing the book, thoughts boiling to the brim with the possibilities, you realize you've lifted the veil for only a femtosecond of humanity's possible future as portrayed in Schismatrix. The conflicts central in humanity's evolution towards Posthumanism and beyond is Darwinian noise—a landscape of ideologies assimilated and rejected. <br /><br />You can see the profound influence on writers (the ones I like and can recall off the top of my head) such as M John Harrison's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17735.Light" title="Light by M. John Harrison" rel="nofollow noopener">Light</a>, Dan Simmons' <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/77566.Hyperion__Hyperion_Cantos___1_" title="Hyperion (Hyperion Cantos, #1) by Dan Simmons" rel="nofollow noopener">Hyperion</a>, Justina Robson's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/735504.Natural_History" title="Natural History by Justina Robson" rel="nofollow noopener">Natural History</a>, amongst others. Rudy Rucker's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/612875.Postsingular" title="Postsingular by Rudy Rucker" rel="nofollow noopener">Postsingular</a>. The scope of imagination is staggering for a book written in 1985. <br /><br />The short stories included in this edition enhances and extrapolates the original text, a series of small revelations in their own right. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11925806252909993516" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

